ion, creation, and reception alongside its continuing afterlife, Tsika examines Dylan’s music in the film through the context of intellectual property, raising questions about who owns artistic material and artistic identities and how such material can be reused and repurposed. Tsika’s adventurous analysis touches on gender, race, queerness, celebrity, popular culture, and the law, while offering much to Haynes and Dylan fans alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBiographical filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picture industryxLaw and legislation. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aTodd Haynes, queer film, Bob Dylan, Cate Blanchett, queer cinema, Velvet Goldmine, filmmaking, biographical film, Grain of Sand, independent film, queer filmmakers, indie film, Far from Heaven, Superstar: The Karen Carpenter Story, film analysis, intellectual property, IP, film soundtrack, film music.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32837840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477328385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477328385/original  a978-3-11-079782-4  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles